{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775901372534,"sessionID":"ses_284083eaaffeJGoSkdYn83qwvG","part":{"id":"prt_d7bf87075001JnB0mGfwBfRAGo","messageID":"msg_d7bf85f080011u8eAdGLsCFf7U","sessionID":"ses_284083eaaffeJGoSkdYn83qwvG","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775901376058,"sessionID":"ses_284083eaaffeJGoSkdYn83qwvG","part":{"id":"prt_d7bf87a92001mH0zXCW9AWygjv","messageID":"msg_d7bf85f080011u8eAdGLsCFf7U","sessionID":"ses_284083eaaffeJGoSkdYn83qwvG","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-98e4c192e4cc496ca1b39dd83654b4a1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/code-execution/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/code-execution/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Code Execution (PicoD) Specification\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: PicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail, manages workspace files, and exposes a health endpoint with JWT (RSA)–protected APIs.\n6: \n7: ## Requirements\n8: \n9: ### Requirement: Command execution API\n10: \n11: The system SHALL accept `POST /api/execute` with a JSON body, run `command[0]` with `command[1:]` as arguments via `exec.CommandContext`, capture stdout and stderr into buffers, and respond with HTTP 200 and an `ExecuteResponse` for successful request handling (including non-zero command exit). The request SHALL NOT accept stdin from the client; the process stdin is not set from the request body.\n12: \n13: #### Scenario: Valid execution with defaults\n14: \n15: - **GIVEN** a valid JWT and JSON body with non-empty `command` and empty `timeout`\n16: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n17: - **THEN** the server uses a default timeout of 60 seconds, runs the command, and returns `stdout`, `stderr`, `exit_code`, `duration` (seconds), `start_time`, and `end_time` as JSON\n18: \n19: #### Scenario: Custom timeout\n20: \n21: - **GIVEN** a valid JWT and JSON body where `timeout` is a non-empty string parseable by Go `time.ParseDuration` (e.g. `\"30s\"`, `\"500ms\"`)\n22: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n23: - **THEN** the server uses that duration for the command context timeout\n24: \n25: #### Scenario: Timeout exceeded\n26: \n27: - **GIVEN** execution exceeds the context deadline\n28: - **WHEN** the context is cancelled\n29: - **THEN** the response `exit_code` SHALL be `124` (`TimeoutExitCode`) and stderr SHALL include a message that the command timed out with the timeout length in seconds (integer formatting)\n30: \n31: #### Scenario: Invalid timeout\n32: \n33: - **GIVEN** `timeout` is non-empty and not a valid duration\n34: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n35: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with JSON `error` describing invalid timeout format and `code` 400\n36: \n37: #### Scenario: Empty command\n38: \n39: - **GIVEN** JSON binds successfully but `command` has length zero\n40: - **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n41: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` `\"command cannot be empty\"` and `code` 400\n42: \n43: #### Scenario: Working directory inside workspace\n44: \n45: - **GIVEN** `working_dir` is non-empty\n46: - **WHEN** the server resolves it with the same path-safety rules as file APIs\n47: - **THEN** `cmd.Dir` is set to the sanitized absolute path; if resolution fails, the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` prefixed by `\"Invalid working directory: \"`\n48: \n49: #### Scenario: Environment augmentation\n50: \n51: - **GIVEN** `env` is non-empty\n52: - **WHEN** the command runs\n53: - **THEN** `cmd.Env` is the current process environment plus additional entries `key=value` for each map entry\n54: \n55: #### Scenario: Malformed JSON\n56: \n57: - **GIVEN** the body is not valid JSON for `ExecuteRequest`\n58: - **WHEN** binding fails\n59: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` from the binder and `code` 400\n60: \n61: ### Requirement: File upload API\n62: \n63: The system SHALL accept `POST /api/files`. If `Content-Type` starts with `multipart/form-data`, the server SHALL treat the request as multipart upload; otherwise it SHALL bind JSON for `UploadFileRequest`.\n64: \n65: #### Scenario: Multipart upload\n66: \n67: - **GIVEN** `Content-Type` has prefix `multipart/form-data`, form field `path` is set, and form file `file` is present\n68: - **WHEN** the client posts to `POST /api/files`\n69: - **THEN** the server creates parent directories with mode `0755`, writes the uploaded stream to a sanitized path, applies mode from form field `mode` via `parseFileMode` (default `0644` when empty/invalid/exceeds max), and responds HTTP 200 with `FileInfo` using `path` as relative to the workspace root\n70: \n71: #### Scenario: Multipart missing path or file\n72: \n73: - **GIVEN** multipart request with empty `path` or missing/unreadable `file`\n74: - **WHEN** the handler runs\n75: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with an appropriate `error` and `code` 400\n76: \n77: #### Scenario: JSON Base64 upload\n78: \n79: - **GIVEN** non-multipart request with JSON `path` and `content` (Base64 standard encoding) required\n80: - **WHEN** the client posts to `POST /api/files`\n81: - **THEN** the server decodes content, creates directories, writes the file with `parseFileMode` on `mode`, and responds HTTP 200 with `FileInfo` (relative `path`)\n82: \n83: #### Scenario: Invalid Base64\n84: \n85: - **GIVEN** JSON upload with invalid Base64 in `content`\n86: - **WHEN** decoding fails\n87: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` describing invalid base64 and `code` 400\n88: \n89: ### Requirement: File listing API\n90: \n91: The system SHALL accept `GET /api/files?path=...`, require the `path` query parameter, read the directory at the sanitized path, and return JSON `ListFilesResponse`.\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: Successful listing\n94: \n95: - **GIVEN** `path` refers to an existing directory inside the workspace\n96: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files?path=<dir>`\n97: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 200 with `files` as an array of `FileEntry` objects (`name`, `size`, `modified`, `mode`, `is_dir`), skipping entries where `entry.Info()` fails\n98: \n99: #### Scenario: Missing query parameter\n100: \n101: - **GIVEN** the `path` query parameter is absent or empty\n102: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files`\n103: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` `\"Missing 'path' query parameter\"` and `code` 400\n104: \n105: #### Scenario: Directory not found\n106: \n107: - **GIVEN** sanitized path does not exist\n108: - **WHEN** `os.ReadDir` fails with not exist\n109: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `error` `\"Directory not found\"` and `code` 404\n110: \n111: ### Requirement: File download API\n112: \n113: The system SHALL serve file contents at `GET /api/files/*path` for a sanitized file path, set download-oriented headers, and stream the file with `c.File`.\n114: \n115: #### Scenario: Successful download\n116: \n117: - **GIVEN** the wildcard path resolves to a regular file inside the workspace\n118: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /api/files/<path>`\n119: - **THEN** the server sets `Content-Description` to `File Transfer`, `Content-Transfer-Encoding` to `binary`, `Content-Disposition` to `attachment; filename=\"<basename>\"`, `Content-Type` from `mime.TypeByExtension` or `application/octet-stream`, and returns the file body\n120: \n121: #### Scenario: Path escapes workspace\n122: \n123: - **GIVEN** the requested path fails `sanitizePath`\n124: - **WHEN** the client calls the download endpoint\n125: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` describing access denied / workspace jail\n126: \n127: #### Scenario: Not a file\n128: \n129: - **GIVEN** the path exists but is a directory\n130: - **WHEN** the client downloads\n131: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 400 with `error` `\"Path is a directory, not a file\"` and `code` 400\n132: \n133: #### Scenario: File missing\n134: \n135: - **GIVEN** the path does not exist\n136: - **WHEN** stat fails with not exist\n137: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 404 with `error` `\"File not found\"` and `code` 404\n138: \n139: ### Requirement: Health endpoint\n140: \n141: The system SHALL expose `GET /health` without JWT middleware and respond HTTP 200 with JSON including `status`, `service`, `version`, and `uptime`.\n142: \n143: #### Scenario: Unauthenticated health\n144: \n145: - **GIVEN** no `Authorization` header\n146: - **WHEN** the client calls `GET /health`\n147: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 200 with `status` `\"ok\"`, `service` `\"PicoD\"`, `version` `\"0.0.1\"`, and `uptime` as a string from `time.Since(server start)`\n148: \n149: ### Requirement: JWT authentication for API routes\n150: \n151: The system SHALL register `/api` routes under a Gin group that uses `AuthManager.AuthMiddleware`. The middleware SHALL require header `Authorization: Bearer <token>`, parse the JWT with an RSA public key, and reject non-RSA signing methods. Valid tokens SHALL allow the request to proceed; after validation the request body SHALL be wrapped with `http.MaxBytesReader` limiting size to `MaxBodySize`.\n152: \n153: #### Scenario: Missing or malformed Authorization\n154: \n155: - **GIVEN** missing header, or a header that is not exactly two space-separated parts with first part `Bearer`\n156: - **WHEN** an `/api` route is hit\n157: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 401 with JSON including `error`, `code` 401, and `detail` explaining the failure\n158: \n159: #### Scenario: Invalid or expired JWT\n160: \n161: - **GIVEN** a Bearer token that fails verification (signature, expiry, etc.) with options `WithExpirationRequired`, `WithIssuedAt`, and `WithLeeway(1 minute)`\n162: - **WHEN** the middleware runs\n163: - **THEN** the server responds HTTP 401 with `error` `\"Invalid token\"`, `code` 401, and `detail` containing the verification error\n164: \n165: #### Scenario: Public key required at startup\n166: \n167: - **GIVEN** `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` is unset or does not decode to an RSA public key in PEM form\n168: - **WHEN** `NewServer` initializes\n169: - **THEN** the process SHALL log a fatal error and not continue serving (there is no unauthenticated API mode when the key is missing)\n170: \n171: ### Requirement: Server configuration\n172: \n173: The system SHALL read CLI flags `-port` and `-workspace`, build `picod.Config`, and listen on `\":<port>\"`. If `workspace` is empty, the workspace root SHALL be the current working directory (fatal if `os.Getwd` fails). The HTTP server SHALL use `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds.\n174: \n175: #### Scenario: Defaults from CLI\n176: \n177: - **GIVEN** `-port` and `-workspace` use program defaults\n178: - **WHEN** the binary starts\n179: - **THEN** `port` defaults to `8080`, `workspace` defaults to empty (resolved to CWD), and Gin runs in `ReleaseMode` with `Logger` and `Recovery` middleware globally\n\n(End of file - total 179 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Code Execution (PicoD) Specification\n\n## Purpose\n\nPicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail, manages workspace files, and exposes a health endpoint with JWT (RSA)–protected APIs.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Command execution API\n\nThe system SHALL accept `POST /api/execute` with a JSON body, run `command[0]` with `command[1:]` as arguments via `exec.CommandContext`, capture stdout and stderr into buffers, and respond with HTTP 200 and an `ExecuteResponse` for successful request handling (including non-zero command exit). The request SHALL NOT accept stdin from the client; the process stdin is not set from the request body.\n\n#### Scenario: Valid execution with defaults\n\n- **GIVEN** a valid JWT and JSON body with non-empty `command` and empty `timeout`\n- **WHEN** the client calls `POST /api/execute`\n- **THEN** the server uses a default timeout of 60 seconds, runs the command, and returns `stdout`, `stderr`, `exit_code`, `duration` (seconds), `start_time`, and `end_time` as JSON\n\n#### Scenario: Custom timeout\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/code-execution/spec.md","time":{"start":1775901376046,"end":1775901376056}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775901376061,"sessionID":"ses_284083eaaffeJGoSkdYn83qwvG","part":{"id":"prt_d7bf87e15001eJRRk4UkY7YtM1","messageID":"msg_d7bf85f080011u8eAdGLsCFf7U","sessionID":"ses_284083eaaffeJGoSkdYn83qwvG","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-9d967d10baa546159d24769bd1e86910","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/deployment/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/deployment/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deployment Specification\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: Deploy AgentCube control-plane components (Workload Manager, Router), optional Volcano agent scheduler, and required Redis connectivity via the `agentcube` Helm chart, container images, and Makefile-driven builds.\n5: \n6: ## Requirements\n7: \n8: ### Requirement: Helm chart installation\n9: The system SHALL support installing/upgrading the AgentCube stack with Helm from `manifests/charts/base`, including namespace creation and values for Redis, images, replicas, and optional router RBAC.\n10: \n11: #### Scenario: Install with release namespace\n12: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster and Helm 3 available\n13: - **WHEN** the operator runs `helm upgrade --install <release> manifests/charts/base --namespace <ns> --create-namespace` with required `redis.addr` (and optional `redis.password`) plus component image overrides as needed\n14: - **THEN** chart templates apply Workload Manager and Router workloads (and optional Volcano resources when enabled) in `<ns>` without manual editing of rendered YAML\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: Helm values and Redis connectivity\n17: The system SHALL require Redis address configuration for Workload Manager and Router at runtime via chart values `redis.addr` and `redis.password` (empty password permitted when Redis has no auth).\n18: \n19: #### Scenario: Components receive Redis env vars\n20: - **GIVEN** `redis.addr` and `redis.password` set in Helm values\n21: - **WHEN** pods for `workloadmanager` and `agentcube-router` start\n22: - **THEN** each container SHALL have environment variables `REDIS_ADDR` and `REDIS_PASSWORD` populated from those values\n23: \n24: ### Requirement: Workload Manager deployment shape\n25: The system SHALL deploy Workload Manager as a `Deployment` and `Service` named `workloadmanager` with replica count, container image, service type/port, resource requests/limits, health probes, and optional `extraEnv` driven from `values.yaml`.\n26: \n27: #### Scenario: Default replica and service exposure\n28: - **GIVEN** default chart values\n29: - **WHEN** the chart is installed\n30: - **THEN** the Workload Manager `Deployment` SHALL use `workloadmanager.replicas` (default 1), expose HTTP on `workloadmanager.service.port` (default 8080), and use liveness/readiness HTTP GET `/health` on that port\n31: \n32: ### Requirement: Router deployment shape\n33: The system SHALL deploy the Router as a `Deployment` and `Service` named `agentcube-router` with replica count, image, `ClusterIP` service mapping `port`→`targetPort`, resource requests/limits, optional dedicated `serviceAccountName`, and `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` pointing at the in-cluster Workload Manager service.\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: Router reaches Workload Manager by DNS\n36: - **GIVEN** release namespace `N` and Workload Manager service port `P` from values\n37: - **WHEN** the Router pod starts\n38: - **THEN** it SHALL have `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL` set to `http://workloadmanager.N.svc.cluster.local:P` and container args including `--port=<targetPort>` and `--debug`\n39: \n40: ### Requirement: Workload Manager ClusterRole permissions\n41: The system SHALL create a `ServiceAccount` `workloadmanager`, a `ClusterRole` `workloadmanager`, and `ClusterRoleBinding` `workloadmanager` granting the rules required for agent-sandbox, AgentCube runtime CRDs, core workloads, auth, and secrets.\n42: \n43: #### Scenario: Binding ties SA to cluster role\n44: - **GIVEN** chart installation in namespace `N`\n45: - **WHEN** RBAC resources are applied\n46: - **THEN** subject `ServiceAccount/workloadmanager` in namespace `N` SHALL be bound to `ClusterRole/workloadmanager` via `ClusterRoleBinding/workloadmanager`\n47: \n48: ### Requirement: Optional Router namespace Role\n49: The system SHALL optionally create namespace-scoped `ServiceAccount`, `Role`, and `RoleBinding` for the Router when `router.rbac.create` is true, granting secret management in that namespace.\n50: \n51: #### Scenario: RBAC off by default\n52: - **GIVEN** `router.rbac.create: false`\n53: - **WHEN** the chart renders templates\n54: - **THEN** Router optional RBAC manifests SHALL NOT be emitted\n55: \n56: #### Scenario: RBAC on with named service account\n57: - **GIVEN** `router.rbac.create: true` and `router.serviceAccountName` set (or defaulted by template to `agentcube-router`)\n58: - **WHEN** the chart is applied\n59: - **THEN** Router pods MAY use that `serviceAccountName` and the Role SHALL allow verbs on `secrets` in the release namespace\n60: \n61: ### Requirement: Optional Volcano agent scheduler\n62: The system SHALL optionally deploy Volcano agent scheduler resources (ServiceAccount, ConfigMap, ClusterRole, ClusterRoleBinding, Service, Deployment) when `volcano.scheduler.enabled` is true.\n63: \n64: #### Scenario: Scheduler disabled\n65: - **GIVEN** `volcano.scheduler.enabled: false` (default)\n66: - **WHEN** templates render\n67: - **THEN** no Volcano scheduler objects SHALL be created\n68: \n69: ### Requirement: CRDs shipped with the chart\n70: The system SHALL ship `CustomResourceDefinition` manifests for `agentruntimes` and `codeinterpreters` under the chart `crds/` directory so Helm installs them with the chart lifecycle.\n71: \n72: #### Scenario: CRD group and scope\n73: - **GIVEN** chart path `manifests/charts/base`\n74: - **WHEN** CRD YAML is applied\n75: - **THEN** both CRDs SHALL use API group `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh`, version `v1alpha1`, and `scope: Namespaced`\n76: \n77: ### Requirement: Docker images for core binaries\n78: The system SHALL provide Dockerfiles to build three images: Workload Manager (`docker/Dockerfile`), Router (`docker/Dockerfile.router`), and picod (`docker/Dockerfile.picod`).\n79: \n80: #### Scenario: Multi-stage Go build for control plane\n81: - **GIVEN** repository root as build context\n82: - **WHEN** `docker build -f docker/Dockerfile` (or `Dockerfile.router`) runs\n83: - **THEN** the image SHALL compile the respective Go binary with `CGO_ENABLED=0` and run it from Alpine 3.19 as a non-root user (`apiserver` UID 1000 or `router` UID 1000) exposing port 8080\n84: \n85: ### Requirement: Makefile build targets\n86: The system SHALL expose Make targets to build binaries (`build`, related targets), run tests (`test`), build/push Docker images (`docker-*`), run code generation (`generate`, `gen-crd`, `gen-client`, `gen-all`, `gen-check`), and run E2E (`e2e`, `e2e-clean`).\n87: \n88: #### Scenario: Default `make` builds workload manager\n89: - **GIVEN** Go toolchain and generated code prerequisites\n90: - **WHEN** the operator runs `make` (default `all` → `build`)\n91: - **THEN** `bin/workloadmanager` SHALL be produced from `./cmd/workload-manager` after `generate`\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: E2E entrypoint\n94: - **GIVEN** Kind, kubectl, Docker, Helm, and curl available\n95: - **WHEN** the operator runs `make e2e`\n96: - **THEN** the repository SHALL execute `./test/e2e/run_e2e.sh` which provisions the cluster (unless skipped), deploys dependencies, and runs Go and Python E2E tests\n\n(End of file - total 96 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deployment Specification\n\n## Purpose\nDeploy AgentCube control-plane components (Workload Manager, Router), optional Volcano agent scheduler, and required Redis connectivity via the `agentcube` Helm chart, container images, and Makefile-driven builds.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Helm chart installation\nThe system SHALL support installing/upgrading the AgentCube stack with Helm from `manifests/charts/base`, including namespace creation and values for Redis, images, replicas, and optional router RBAC.\n\n#### Scenario: Install with release namespace\n- **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster and Helm 3 available\n- **WHEN** the operator runs `helm upgrade --install <release> manifests/charts/base --namespace <ns> --create-namespace` with required `redis.addr` (and optional `redis.password`) plus component image overrides as needed\n- **THEN** chart templates apply Workload Manager and Router workloads (and optional Volcano resources when enabled) in `<ns>` without manual editing of rendered YAML\n\n### Requirement: Helm values and Redis connectivity\nThe system SHALL require Redis address configuration for Workload Manager and Router at runtime via chart values `redis.addr` and `redis.password` (empty password permitted when Redis has no auth).\n\n#### Scenario: Components receive Redis env vars\n- **GIVEN** `redis.addr` and `redis.password` set in Helm values","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/deployment/spec.md","time":{"start":1775901376049,"end":1775901376059}}}}
